  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions developed gradually over several decades:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged as a criminal concept in the 1930s during Prohibition era United States\n- Initially focused on concealing proceeds from illegal activities like bootlegging\n\n2. Key Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major US legislation requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO) (1970) - Expanded legal tools to combat organized crime financing\n\n3. International Milestones:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention - First international treaty addressing money laundering\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989 to develop global anti-money laundering standards\n\n4. Modern Regulatory Framework:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - Significantly expanded money laundering reporting requirements\n- Comprehensive regulations requiring:\n- Customer identification\n- Transaction monitoring\n- Suspicious activity reporting\n- International information sharing\n\n5. Global Expansion:\n- Most developed countries now have comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) legal frameworks\n- Increasing cooperation between international law enforcement agencies\n\nThe legal approach has progressively become more sophisticated, technologically advanced, and internationally coordinated.",
